## Welcome Aboard

December 2025, I'm in Tokyo for the first time. Someone on my Instagram feed 
had already told me what to do before I landed: download Google Maps, it 
has the most accurate Yamanote Line schedule. I did it, mostly out of 
curiosity.

The train came exactly when it said it would. Then the next one. Then the 
one after that. Two weeks riding that loop around the city and I never once 
pulled out my phone to check if something was running late, because nothing 
was. The schedule was just accurate. That was the whole thing.

I came home to New York and opened the MTA app out of habit. Delayed.

That contrast is what this project is actually about. Not a complaint — a 
real question: why does one system do what it says it's going to do, and 
the other treat its own schedule like a rough suggestion? The answer goes 
deeper than punctuality. It gets into how each system is physically built, 
how demand moves through it, how often trains actually come, and — maybe 
most surprisingly — what each city chooses to measure and share about how 
it's performing at all.

Four things this piece is going to get into:

- Why the physical layout of each system, a branching web versus a closed 
  loop, shapes almost everything else
- Where and when each city actually moves its riders, and what the data gap 
  between them reveals
- What "frequent" really means and why consistent service matters more than 
  peak service
- What reliability data each city publishes, what it keeps quiet, and what 
  both of those choices tell you

One note before we go: these two systems are not perfectly comparable, and 
this project doesn't pretend otherwise. The MTA publishes hourly ridership 
for every station, monthly on-time performance by line, and full schedule 
data as open data. JR East publishes annual station totals and schedules, 
but no hourly ridership and no delay archives. Where direct comparison isn't 
possible, the charts show what is comparable and name the gap. That 
asymmetry is a finding, not just a limitation.

::: {.callout-note appearance="minimal"}
*How do service design and demand patterns differ between the BMT and the 
Yamanote Line, and what does that suggest about reliability and passenger 
experience?*
:::

